<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> THE ADVANTAGEOUS ADVENTURE PATH, PART II (SITES 4-9)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.58)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495'>Devon "Devonator" Clark</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 13, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> This is the continuation of my earlier article, “The Advantageous Adventure Path, Sites 1-3” and it explores the pros and cons of the many various sites that are at our disposal when we build our decks.  Sites 1 to 3 focused a lot on setting up our strategy for the more dangerous parts of our journey by allowing us to draw cards when we meet certain criteria, or by reducing twilight, or by allowing us to download cards.  Some of the sites hereafter have similar abilities, but for the most part the rest of the path will focus on the shadow engine and defensive measures.  So, I propose we break camp and continue our journey along the Advantageous Adventure Path . . . <br />
<br />
Site 4<br />
We begin the second leg of our journey by visiting Moria and the surrounding mountains.  Strangely enough many people look at site 4 as a throwaway site.  There really aren’t many “powerful” site 4s, so we might not give much consideration to our choice there.  However, site 4 sets up our shadow phase at the bridge and doing the most damage possible there (or limiting the damage that our opponent does) is a very important part of a deck’s success.  And many players will base their choice for site 4 solely on whether or not they are playing the Cave Troll.<br />
<br />
Balin’s Tomb<br />
3--Discard a tale to heal a companion (Underground)<br />
Balin’s Tomb is a fellowship strengthening site 4.  But we’ve now reached the leg of our journey where it is more beneficial to our deck to help the shadow.  For that reason, this site really only fits into non-Moria Dwarven decks, because it can help the fellowship a lot.  And since effective Dwarven Decks are so rare, Balin’s Tomb is just about 99% guaranteed not to help your opponent.<br />
<br />
Dwarrowdelf Chamber<br />
2--When you move to Dwarrowdelf, exert Gimli or 2 other companions. (Underground)<br />
Gimli is a rare starting companion . . . so against most decks, Dwarrowdelf will lead to 2 companions exerting.  And any extra wound tokens make it harder to heal completely at the next sanctuary, even if they are on non-fighting companions.  The drawbacks to this site are the reduced twilight number (1 twilight can make a very big difference . . . especially if site 3 was the Courtyard), its limited usefulness (as it only really fits in decks that start Gimli), and that many of the other site 4s will be a better fit for your deck.<br />
<br />
Eregion Hills<br />
2--When the fellowship moves here, add a burden<br />
Any deck that plays burden dependent cards will find great use in this site 4 because anybody who has played burden dependent decks knows that 1 burden can be the difference between victory and defeat.  Unfortunately, for that burden, you sacrifice 1 twilight.  But even so, that is typically a beneficial tradeoff for any burden dependent deck (Twilight Nazgul are a possible exception).  Also, this site is not underground, so it provides your fellowship with a little bit of extra Cave Troll protection.  <br />
<br />
Great Chasm<br />
4--The cost of the first Moria culture archer played here is –2 (Underground)<br />
This site is intended for Moria Archery decks, as it gives the twilight intensive shadow side a second Dimrill Dale (or would that be a first) and the single highest shadow number of all site 4s.  With its shadow number and cost reduction, the Great Chasm empowers Moria Archery strategies with (in essence) an additional 3 twilight.  Of course, the Great Chasm’s usefulness is not exclusive to Moria Archery decks.  A higher twilight number can easily benefit any twilight intensive shadow side.  Just be sure that your fellowship can handle Moria Archery . . . and the Cave Troll.<br />
<br />
Hollin<br />
3--Uruk-hai are not roaming (Plains)<br />
Hollin is a staple of many Uruk-hai decks.  With its shadow number of 3 and reduced Uruk-hai costs, your Isengard deck can pump out an additional 1 or 2 Uruk-hai at this site (and like Nazgul, extra Uruk-hai are very dangerous).  The drawback is that, if your opponent is playing Uruk-hai, they will benefit from your site 4 as well, and since you are probably trailing the race and Uruk-hai are famous for their stopping power, your fellowship might be in some serious trouble.<br />
<br />
Mithril Mine<br />
3--Remove 1 to play a shadow possession from your discard pile (Underground)<br />
This site 4 can fit into any deck that utilizes shadow weapons, as it’s a less expensive, one-site Relics of Moria.  Of course, it fits best into Moria decks that play Scimitars and Armories, as you can basically play cards, draw cards, and generate twilight using this sites text.  This site also goes well in an Isengard Orc deck, as Isengard Axes don’t need other conditions to play for free.  The drawbacks are that if you use this site in a non-Moria deck, you open yourself up to the Cave Troll.  And if you play a Moria deck, with Scavengers, Hosts, TAC, and Relics, you often have many ways to pull weapons back without the site, so Moria Stairway could be a more effective site 4.<br />
<br />
Moria Lake<br />
3--When you move to Moria Lake, exert Frodo or 2 other companions (Marsh)<br />
Moria Lake is another site that creates wounds on its own, so like Dwarrowdelf and Midgewater Marshes this site fits well into a Sauron direct damage deck.  It also fits well into a Twilight Nazgul deck because Twilight Nazgul create burdens by wounding or forcing the ring-bearer to exert, thus the additional twilight and wound could be more beneficial than Eregion Hills.  Therefore, because of its shadow number, the fact that it’s not underground, and that it forces a mandatory companion to exert, Moria Lake makes it into many decks because it’s a bit of a neutral site 4.<br />
<br />
Moria Stairway<br />
2--Companions or Minions bearing hand weapons are damage +1 (Underground)<br />
Moria Stairway, like Ettenmoors for site 2s, can be the most devastating site 4 if used in the right deck.  A Cave Troll with Hammer is Damage +3 and fierce here.  Furthermore, this site makes Scavengers and Relics invaluable as all of your weapon-carrying Orcs become killing machines.  At the very least, you’ll draw archery fire and that sets up sites 5 and 6 as killing grounds.  Of course, you must build your fellowship so that it can survive those same attacks.  Lurtz with his sword at the Stairway could spell game-over if you haven’t established your fellowship.<br />
<br />
Pass of Caradhras<br />
3--Play a weather condition from your draw deck (Mountain)<br />
The fact that this site is a Mountain means nothing yet.  Though I’m sure that in future sets Mountains may be of great impact.  This site allows you to guarantee a weather condition at site 4 and that will be of greater consequence as we see more Saruman/Weather decks.  Currently, the only weather conditions that really stand out are Wizard Storm and Saruman’s Snows, but a creative deck-builder could create a very powerful deck type using some of the more underrated Weather Conditions.  Still, most Uruk-hai decks will continue to run Hollin, and most Isengard Orc decks will probably run Moria Lake or the Mithril Mine.<br />
<br />
Site 5<br />
We now reach the mid-point of our journey and one of the only constants in the game, so know the shadow number and text, and plan accordingly.  If your opponent plays the Balrog, you will probably see it here.  That’s not that bad, even if it’s the rare Balrog, because you know it won’t follow you.  Otherwise, this site will give Nazgul, Isengard Orc, and Sauron players each chances to drop multiple minions on you, so it’s typically a bad idea to enter the Bridge with any trailing minions.  Furthermore, Uruk-hai stop roaming, so it’s a bad idea to enter with any trailing twilight.  In other words, it’s typically a bad idea to double to 5, AND it’s a bad idea to add a lot to the pool when moving to the Bridge.  But, you gain an advantage in the Bridge.  You know what’s coming.  So, simply be prepared and plan accordingly.  Oh, and for any newbies reading this, here’s the site description…<br />
<br />
The Bridge of Khazad-dum<br />
6--Play the Balrog from your deck or hand; the Balrog costs –6 (Underground)<br />
You have to play it; so don’t even bother looking at the pros and cons.  Instead ask yourself if you want to play the Balrog.  If you’re playing Moria, the question becomes whether or not you want to shuffle.  So, typically, you want to play the Balrog, but there are some exceptions.  In other decks, your opponent is going to usually give you 10+ twilight and I say use it.  The common Balrog will only cost 6; and furthermore, it won’t move any cards in your hand.  On the other hand, it is a guaranteed baddie at site 5.<br />
<br />
Site 6<br />
We reach the second (and last) sanctuary on our journey . . . BUT we haven’t healed yet.  There’s still a lot of damage to be done here.  More importantly, this site begins the home stretch, and strategically, this site should be the focus of your deck design . . . Either kill companions before site 6 or ensure that your companions survive through site 6.  Accomplish one of those 2 goals and you should win the game.  Another important factor to consider is that Site 6 begins our trek along the Anduin River and that means that ARV is a factor once again.<br />
<br />
Caras Galadhon<br />
3--While the fellowship is here, only 1 minion may be assigned to any skirmish (Forest)<br />
This site was designed to combat swarms.  But the effects of it run deeper than simply preventing multiple minions from overwhelming your companions.  Since you have no fear of extra minions, this site saves you archery exertions.  It allows a player that knows he is moving to Caras Galadhon to use the twilight pool at his leisure with no fear of having to face more than he can handle . . . AND any wounds he takes here will get healed.  Of course, you don’t want to play this site in any deck that could swarm.<br />
<br />
Dimrill Dale<br />
3--The first Moria Orc played at Dimrill Dale costs -2<br />
Dimrill Dale presents the Moria shadow player with a sort of Ford of Bruinen for Moria Orcs.  As such, it is a particularly effective site 6 since 2 extra twilight can be the difference between a Cave Troll or no Cave Troll . . . which in the grand scheme of Moria can be the difference between winning and losing.  It is EXTREMELY important to be able to damage your opponent here, as good fellowships will double move right past the Balrog.  Of course, if you are playing Moria, there is absolutely no surprise to this site, and that will often limit its effectiveness.  Also, with many of the popular orcs costing 1, the Dale’s text is often wasted.  This is one of two site 6s that do not meet the criteria for ARV.<br />
<br />
Galadriel’s Glade<br />
3--Exert an Elf to look at an opponent’s hand<br />
Many people have asked me why I run the Glade as my site 6 in a lot of decks.  “It doesn’t do anything,” they say; to which Steve Alwine would reply, “Correction!  It does nothing.”  The most important factor in the Glade’s usefulness . . . is its lack of usefulness.  It is NOT a river or forest.  Even with the errata to ARV, that card is still a factor in the meta, and selecting your site path carefully can be a counter to that common opposing strategy.  The Glade does not benefit you, nor does it benefit your opponent.  And the latter part is its strength.  However, do not let the Glade’s lack of usefulness breed complacency in you.  The site’s text is there to be used, and it can win games.  <br />
<br />
Lothlorien Woods<br />
3--Site 6 allies are power +3 (Forest)<br />
Site 6 ally decks are very powerful.  Using cards like the Horn of Boromir, Swan-Ship of the Galadhrim, and/or One Whom Men Would Follow, you can turn your allies into makeshift companions to keep your fellowship alive and kicking.  This site can make these deck types even more powerful . . . especially if your running Uruviel.  The biggest drawback to this site is that many of your site 6 ally decks would like to incorporate Gift of Boats . . . in which case you must play Valley of the Silverlode.  And furthermore, if you’re not playing Uruviel (which most decks don’t) this site’s text is a one-shot deal . . . and that isn’t very helpful.<br />
<br />
Valley of the Silverlode<br />
3--When you move here, you may heal every Hobbit companion (River)<br />
Any deck that plays Gift of Boats has got to play Valley of the Silverlode to set up the triple move.  Any deck that relies heavily on hobbit exertions will want to play Valley of the Sivlerlode to make their fellowship more effective.  And even if neither of these are the case, this site adds to the number of wounds you heal before you start the next leg of your journey.  Of course, it benefits your opponent also . . . And it is a river.<br />
<br />
Site 7<br />
In Part 1 of the Advantageous Adventure Path, I mentioned that there are three site selections, which are more important than any of the rest and will define your adventure path.  Site 7 is the second of those three and it is very important because you can use site 7 to counter some of the more powerful strategies used against you.<br />
<br />
Anduin Confluence<br />
6--When the fellowship moves here, discard every ally (River)<br />
The Confluence can cripple decks that rely on allies to preserve their fellowship over the last few sites.  However, despite its often-devastating text, the Confluence is not all-powerful as those allies are only discarded.  They do not go to the dead pile.  So, your opponent can play them again.  Therefore, this site is an Ally speed bump . . . not an Ally red light.  Unfortunately, most decks rely on allies in one way or another and that makes this a rare find in the tournament environment.  But, for that reason, if you can fit this site into your Adventure Path, this site can be a tournament winner!<br />
<br />
Anduin Wilderland<br />
6--Skip the Archery Phase (Forest, River)<br />
Just as the Confluence can cripple most ally decks, the Wilderland can drop the hammer on decks that rely on Archery.  By eliminating the archery phase all together (even if it’s only for one site), you can derail the White Arrows of Lorien, Orc Bowmen, Moria Archery, and more.  Furthermore, the Wilderland can be used with your shadow side as an offensive weapon.  Very many Moria overwhelms happen at the Wilderland, because Moria can easily get more minions out than the fellowship has companions.  Archery is the most common defense against this.  Thus, by eliminating the means of removing excess minions, you open the door for an overwhelm.  Of course, if your fellowship doesn’t have an alternate means of taking care of excess minions, this may not be the wisest site 7 to play.<br />
<br />
The Great River<br />
6--While the fellowship is here, cards may not be played from your draw deck or discard pile (River)<br />
The Great River was designed to hinder Moria Swarms.  And to that end, it is very effective.  It’s also a neutral site 7, as it doesn’t stand to seriously damage any deck strategies as the other three site 7s can.  That makes this site both better and worse than the other site 7s.  In other words, this is your site 7, when the other three don’t fit (e.g., a Hobbit Hospital/Sauron Bowmen deck).<br />
<br />
Silverlode Banks<br />
6--When the fellowship moves here, spot a Ranger or exert every companion (River)<br />
If you can eliminate all of your opponent’s rangers, this is an extremely powerful site 7.  However, Aragorn is a ranger and particularly difficult to kill, so this is not an easy task.  And since most decks play Aragorn just because of the Pony’s prevalence, the “Spot a ranger” criterion is typically met and that makes this site, like the Great River, a neutral site 7.  <br />
<br />
Site 8<br />
Site 8 is often a strategic footnote for a deck.  I say that, because many people believe that the double move from 7 to 9 is the easiest double in the game . . . and often rightly so.  Of course, this is complicated by the Shores of Nen Hithoel.  <br />
<br />
Anduin Banks<br />
6--Add 2 to the Minion Archery total for every companion over 4 (River)<br />
Anduin Banks is a bit of an enigmatic site 6.  Its game text is devastating against a lot of decks.  However, when you get down to the trade-offs, you often begin to wonder if there mightn’t be a more appropriate site 8.  With Moria and Nazgul, this site fits because large fellowships are typically a problem.  However, Nazgul are a twilight intensive shadow; therefore the extra twilight generated by a Gates of Argonath or Shores of Nen Hithoel is often more valuable than an undetermined number of wounds.  Now, Moria doesn’t suffer from the twilight efficiency bug . . . still, they might pass over the Banks in favor of the Shores of Nen Hithoel.  Sauron and Isengard are probably best fit to the banks because (at this stage) they’re twilight intensiveness has gone away AND they can’t reliably trigger the Shores so this site enters the picture.  However, both Isengard and Sauron are famous for killing companions, so the text will often not come into effect.  Again, the upside of this side is incredibly high, but the trade-offs make this site a difficult choice.<br />
<br />
Brown Lands<br />
6--Add 1 to the Minion Archery total for every Minion Archer here (River)<br />
Only Isengard and Moria have minion archers, so unless you have plans of using this as a neutral site, you should only play the Brown Lands with an Isengard or Moria Archery deck.  However, Isengard only has 2 archers (both of which are expensive and unique) so it really isn’t viable.  Therefore, this deck really only belongs in Moria Archery . . . and in Moria Archery the entire focus of the shadow is the Brown Lands.  Why?  Because Moria Archery can easily achieve 6 or more free wounds at this site!  Meanwhile, on the fellowship side, because this site only works with Moria Archery, and because Moria Archery is relatively rare, there’s little to no chance that this site selection will come back to bite you.  (Note to new players: Orc Bowmen and the Brown Lands don’t work together.)<br />
<br />
Gates of Argonath<br />
8--Maneuver Events May Not Be Played (River)<br />
The Gates of Argonath is a welcome addition to the site pool because it adds another high shadow number site AND it gives us a way to stop ARV at every site.  Furthermore, while Shores of Nen Hithoel was popular because of its high shadow number, we ran a risk of being stopped by the site 8 text.  Now, we no longer have to fear our own site 8.  Of course, in exchange for this reliability, we sacrifice all of our useful Maneuver events (Hate, Valiant Man of the West, A Ranger’s Versatility, One of You Must Do This, etc.) but then again, so do our opponents.<br />
<br />
Pillars of the King<br />
6--Discard a Gondor card to heal a Gondor companion (River)<br />
Pillars of the King is another enigmatic site like the Anduin Banks.  It has a very large upside AND a very large downside.  The Pillars of the King works best in decks that run a fast fellowship with some kind of site control.  If a deck does not have both of those elements, it runs the risk of losing to the Pillars’ text as Aragorn reloads his Bow with Atheli, Shards of Narsil, and clones of Boromir.  So, if your fellowship defines the path but doesn’t run, your opponent will get the benefit of your site 8 but not you; and if you run but don’t define the path, you’ll continually play on your opponent’s site 8.  So, if you play the Pillars of the King, make sure your deck does both.<br />
<br />
Shores of Nen Hithoel<br />
9--Spot 5 orcs to prevent the free people’s player from moving again (River)<br />
Contrary to popular belief, getting 5 orcs into play at one time is no easy task . . . except for Moria . . . with Isengard or Sauron, 5 orcs depends on either incredible luck or a card drawing engine.  So, unless your playing Moria, you’re not playing the Shores for its text . . . and if you’re playing the site for its twilight number, you might prefer the Gates of Argonath, because then you don’t have to worry about losing to your own site.  On the other hand, if you ARE playing Moria, the Shores can be that extra bit of offense you need to win a close game.  Just remember the same holds true against you.  <br />
<br />
Site 9<br />
Finally, the fellowship has reached the end of the path . . . but they have not yet survived it.  On one hand, the fellowship player is at an advantage because only “a” ringbearer needs to escape.  On the other hand, powerful site texts and large twilight numbers counterbalance the fellowship’s seeming advantages with a host of shadow nastiness.  All this and the fact that site 9 is the focus of the entire game makes site 9 as important a site as site 1.  <br />
<br />
Emyn Muil<br />
9--Exert a minion to make that minion fierce<br />
With the Emyn Muil’s text, a shadow player can easily turn 4 minions into a makeshift Moria swarm.  By sacrificing points of vitality, that player creates extra skirmish phases with those minions.  However, the makeshift swarm isn’t quite as versatile as an actual swarm.  If those minions can’t kill companions in the first round, there’s no way to make the ringbearer fight.  And furthermore, you’ll need the majority of those fierce minions to survive to the fierce skirmishes in order for them to prove effective.  Finally, the make shift swarm suffers from the greatest weakness of the Moria swarm--Archery.  For that reason, you’ll need some means of either preventing wounds or canceling the archery phase.<br />
<br />
Slopes of Amon Hen<br />
9--Isengard Minions cost –1<br />
There are 2 shadow sides that compliment this site--Uruk-hai and Isengard Orcs.  With the high shadow number and cost reduction, a shadow player can easily afford 5+ minions.  However, Isengard is not Moria and that means that a shadow player often leaves himself at the mercy of luck as to which minions he’ll be able to play at the later sites . . . and more so here than with other sites since the focus of the Slopes is to allow you to drop your entire shadow hand as opposed to getting the most out of each card that you play (i.e., Wastes of Emyn Muil and Emyn Muil); therefore if you choose to play this site, make sure to design your shadow with cards that maximize the efficiency of each card and eliminate luck.<br />
<br />
Summit of Amon Hen<br />
8--Draw a card for every burden on the Ring-Bearer<br />
This site obviously benefits burdening strategies . . . but it can benefit any shadow because all shadow sides have the possibility of adding burdens; therefore for every burden that you add, you increase your chances of having the necessary cards at site 9.  Increased hand size always results in increased deck efficiency; therefore this site will never hurt your shadow.  However, the drawbacks to this site are its reduced shadow number and the fact that the best players in the tournament environment know to avoid burdens or remove them.  <br />
<br />
Tol Brandir<br />
9--Play 3 trackers from your discard pile and end your shadow phase (River)<br />
Isengard and Sauron have trackers . . . other shadows do not.  Therefore, this site will primarily help them.  Basically, if you count on your typical card distribution, you should have 5+ shadow cards at site 9 (this may seem counterintuitive, but trust me that’s accurate); therefore you should be able to play 2 or 3 minions from your hand.  Then, since you are playing either of the shadow sides most renowned for killing companions, adding 3 minions from your discard pile will (in most cases) translate into Frodo skirmishing and often being overwhelmed.  However, to counterbalance this incredible power, Tol Brandir is a river and therefore the only site 9 subject to A Ranger’s Versatility.<br />
<br />
Wastes of Emyn Muil<br />
9--Spot 4 companions and exert your Isengard Orc to make the Free People’s player wound a companion<br />
Wastes of the Emyn Muil moves the Regroup phase ability of most Isengard Orcs to the Maneuver phase.  The benefit of that is that it allows ALL Isengard Orcs to join the fun (even your Orc Shamans can do some damage) and that allows you to kill more companions so you might be able to pile more minions on the ringbearer.  On the other hand, it opens your minions up to Archery or other means of wounding and that can result in your stronger minions being targeted for removal.<br />
<br />
<br />
And that brings us to the end of the adventure path.  I realize that some of you might feel that I have underemphasized certain site dependent factors (e.g., Black Steeds and the Watcher in the Water); however I tried to only focus on game mechanics that “will” affect your site selections.  Still, I hope you have enjoyed your tour thus far.  For the remainder of our journey, I will be splitting you into two groups with two new tour guides--Gollum and Theoden.  So, until next time, it has been my pleasure . . . <br />
<br />
. . . Oh!  Those of you going with Gollum, watch those ring fingers!<br />
